  "topic_name": "Heat",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Heat is a form of energy that flows from a hotter object to a colder object. Temperature is the measure of how hot or cold an object is. Heat and temperature are related but different - heat is energy while temperature is a measurement. A thermometer is used to measure temperature. Heat is transferred in three ways: conduction (through solids by particle vibration), convection (through fluids by particle movement), and radiation (through empty space without any medium). Materials that allow heat to pass through easily are called conductors of heat (metals). Materials that do not allow heat to pass through easily are called insulators (wood, plastic, air).",
    "rules": [
      "Heat is a form of energy.",
      "Heat flows from hot objects to cold objects.",
      "Temperature measures how hot or cold an object is.",
      "A thermometer is used to measure temperature.",
      "Celsius and Fahrenheit are temperature scales.",
      "Conduction transfers heat through solids.",
      "Convection transfers heat through liquids and gases.",
      "Radiation transfers heat without any medium.",
      "Good conductors of heat: metals like iron, copper, aluminum.",
      "Poor conductors (insulators): wood, plastic, rubber, air, wool."
    ]
  },
